📘 What is Pagination in Rails?

Pagination means splitting a large set of records into smaller chunks (pages) instead of loading everything at once.

For example:
If you have 10,000 users, you don’t want to load all of them on one page. Instead:

Page 1 → 20 users

Page 2 → next 20 users

Page 3 → next 20 users
and so on…

This improves:

✅ Performance

✅ Memory usage

✅ User experience

🔹 How Pagination Works Internally

At database level, pagination uses:

LIMIT 20 OFFSET 40;

Meaning:

LIMIT → how many records

OFFSET → how many to skip

In Rails (ActiveRecord), this becomes:

User.limit(20).offset(40)
🔹 Pagination in Rails

Rails does not provide built-in pagination UI helpers, so we use gems.

The two most popular gems:

Kaminari

will_paginate

🔹 Using Kaminari (Most Common Today)
1️⃣ Add gem
gem 'kaminari'
bundle install
2️⃣ Controller
def index
  @users = User.page(params[:page]).per(10)
end

Explanation:

.page(params[:page]) → which page number

.per(10) → records per page

3️⃣ View
<%= paginate @users %>

This automatically generates:

Previous button

Next button

Page numbers

🔹 Example Flow

URL:

/users?page=3

Controller:

@users = User.page(3).per(10)

SQL generated:

SELECT * FROM users LIMIT 10 OFFSET 20;

Because:

OFFSET = (page - 1) * per_page
OFFSET = (3 - 1) * 10 = 20
🔹 Using will_paginate

Controller:

@users = User.paginate(page: params[:page], per_page: 10)

View:

<%= will_paginate @users %>
🔹 When To Use Pagination?

In your Learn Module app (courses, programs, users, enrollments):

Users listing page

Courses catalog

Admin dashboard

Logs

Search results

🔹 Important Interview Points

If interviewer asks:

💡 Why pagination?

Reduces DB load

Prevents large memory allocation

Faster page response

💡 What problem with large OFFSET?

For very large tables:

OFFSET 100000 becomes slow

Database scans many rows

Solution:

Cursor-based pagination

Use indexed columns (like id)

Example:

User.where("id > ?", last_seen_id).limit(10)

This is faster for large datasets.

🔹 Types of Pagination

| Type            | When Used            |
| --------------- | -------------------- |
| Offset-based    | Normal UI pagination |
| Cursor-based    | APIs, large datasets |
| Infinite Scroll | Modern frontend apps |


🔹 Quick Interview 30-sec Answer

Pagination in Rails is used to divide large datasets into smaller pages to improve performance and user experience. It’s usually implemented using gems like Kaminari or will_paginate, which internally use LIMIT and OFFSET in SQL. For large datasets, cursor-based pagination is preferred for better performance.

